On Tuesday, shortly after Elon Musk=E2=80=99s extraordinary press
avail in the Oval Office=E2=80=94the unfounded declarations about fraud and=
 corruption; the bizarro appearance of his 4-year-old son, X =C3=86 A-Xii (=
X for short); a bemused Trump looking on=E2=80=94the retired CBS News White=
 House correspondent Peter Maer sought to contextualize the gravity of the =
moment in a Facebook post. =E2=80=9CIn my years on the White House beat fro=
m Presidents Carter to Obama,=E2=80=9D he wrote, =E2=80=9CI never witnessed=
 a scene
like the disgusting display that occurred in the Oval Office today.=E2=80=
=9D

=C2=A0

Whatever one made of Elon=E2=80=99s appearance, it was indisputably abnorma=
l and historic. Fittingly, the images went viral on social media, and led p=
ractically all the major news sites on Tuesday afternoon. At 6:30 p.m., ABC=
=E2=80=99s David Muir began World News Tonight with =E2=80=9Cbreaking news=
=E2=80=9D of the =E2=80=9Cremarkable scene
just a short time ago: Elon Musk holding court in the Oval Office.=E2=80=9D=
 Likewise, NBC=E2=80=99s Lester Holt led the Nightly News with Musk=E2=80=
=99s =E2=80=9Cmajor moment with President Trump in the Oval Office.=E2=80=
=9D

=C2=A0

Notably, CBS took a different tack, delivered by Evening News co-host John =
Dickerson: =E2=80=9CWe begin tonight with a classic question that has come =
to symbolize a crisis in
American education: Why can=E2=80=99t Johnny read?=E2=80=9D The package was=
 pegged to national test scores demonstrating that students remain at pre-p=
andemic reading levels despite hundreds of billions of dollars in federal p=
andemic relief funds. After the six-minute segment, Dickerson and his co-ho=
st Maurice DuBois offered a =E2=80=9Croundup=E2=80=9D of the day=E2=80=99s =
headlines, noting Russia=E2=80=99s release of an American prisoner (15 seco=
nds) and Musk=E2=80=99s Oval appearance (22 seconds), before moving on to a=
 two-minute
conversation with CBS=E2=80=99s chief medical correspondent about Avian flu=
=2E

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CWhy can=E2=80=99t Johnny read?=E2=80=9D is a play on the 1955 best=
-selling book about flaws in U.S. education, of course. But within CBS=E2=
=80=99s Washington bureau, it has become fodder for a broader internal crit=
ique of Evening News=E2=80=94and, indeed, the network itself=E2=80=94under =
C.E.O. Wendy McMahon and Evening News supervising
producer Bill Owens. =E2=80=9CWhy can=E2=80=99t John read the news?=E2=80=
=9D one CBS News correspondent asked me, referring to Dickerson. =E2=80=9CI=
t=E2=80=99s tough to watch,=E2=80=9D a former CBS News insider said. =E2=80=
=9CI appreciate doing something new. I really do=E2=80=A6 [but] Bill and I =
have different theories of the case.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Since becoming CBS News C.E.O. in 2023, McMahon has entrusted the network=
=E2=80=99s editorial vision to Owens, which is
understandable given his tenure at 60 Minutes, where he has served as execu=
tive producer since 2019. Last August, she expanded Owens=E2=80=99 remit to=
 include Evening News, the perennial third-place nightly news broadcast. Ow=
ens immediately conceived of a new editorial strategy prioritizing longer e=
nterprise packages, human interest stories, and ample weather coverage over=
 the usual digest of the day=E2=80=99s big headlines. He also asked McMahon=
 to delicately transfer Norah O=E2=80=99Donnell
off the anchor=E2=80=99s desk in order to install Dickerson and DuBois, mak=
ing Evening News the first nightly broadcast to do away with a single ancho=
r, Cronkite nostalgia be damned.

=C2=A0

Perhaps none of these were great ideas, but they were at least an attempt t=
o shake up a stale format whose decline mirrors the demise of linear televi=
sion. While it=E2=80=99s obviously very early=E2=80=94the newly revamped
Evening News only debuted in late January=E2=80=94the show has already seen=
 its ratings markedly decline. In its second week, its total audience was d=
own 5 percent from the prior week, and down 9 percent year over year. Meanw=
hile, the programming strategy has confounded many network insiders=E2=80=
=94=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just not good, sorry=E2=80=9D one said=E2=80=94whi=
le irking several of the Washington-based correspondents, who fear the loss=
 of what precious little real estate still exists for their work.=C2=A0

Shari=E2=80=99s Trump Treaty
----------------------

Ironically, the pivot to less headline-driven programming is occurring at a
moment when real news is coming out of Washington at a record clip. On Wedn=
esday morning, I=E2=80=99m told that Owens came down to the newsroom floor =
and made it clear to executive producer Guy Campanile and others that even =
he thought the broadcast had underplayed the Musk news. Was this ass-coveri=
ng, an actual volte-face, or simply the latest sign that no one in charge r=
eally knows what to do anymore? =E2=80=9CI think last night was the night m=
any around here really got
upset or confused by what they=E2=80=99re attempting to do,=E2=80=9D one CB=
S News insider told me.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In the grand scheme of things, Evening News certainly did need an overhaul,=
 and it could afford to take the risk. And, given all the myriad ways peopl=
e now get their news, you can understand the desire to create a product tha=
t offered something other than headlines that audiences are already
familiar with by 6:30 p.m. If 60 Minutes and CBS Sunday Mornings have prove=
n successful with the newsmagazine format, the logic goes, then why not Eve=
ning News? The longer packages seemed designed for social media and YouTube=
, which is where the future of the format resides.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Then again, Evening News remains a profitable enterprise watched by nearly =
5 million
people, and, as most media veterans see it, there=E2=80=99s a reason why th=
at=E2=80=99s the case. Alas, Owens=E2=80=99 newsmagazine format =E2=80=9Cdo=
es not work at that time,=E2=80=9D one longtime media exec said. =E2=80=9CT=
here=E2=80=99s a reason formats work where they work.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In any event, the frustrations over Evening News are compounding the larger=
 problems at CBS News amid the recent 60 Minutes edit
scandal ( https://puck.news/cbs-news-divided-on-trump-lawsuit-settlement/?u=
tm_campaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+=
The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), and the broader anxieties=
 about the news division=E2=80=99s fate if and when (when, really) Paramoun=
t is sold ( https://puck.news/will-trumps-fcc-chair-kill-the-paramount-skyd=
ance-deal/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_c=
ontent=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_act=
ion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to Skydance. A=
s I noted last week, everyone at the network, including Wendy and Bill, opp=
oses Shari
Redstone=E2=80=99s plan to settle Trump=E2=80=99s nonsensical election inte=
rference lawsuit against the network and views it as a gross incursion on p=
ress freedom. At the same time, many in the newsroom are also frustrated wi=
th Owens for making the unforced error and leaving the network vulnerable i=
n the first place. Of course, the great irony in all this is that while Tru=
mp bullies and intimidates CBS News, he is hardly likely to deprive his loy=
al supporter and donor Larry Ellison
and his son David of the asset.=C2=A0

Still, the 60 scandal and the aimlessness of Evening News have taken some o=
f the shine off the Tiffany network, adding insult to injury for journalist=
s struggling to come to terms with the real existential crisis=E2=80=94whic=
h, as I=E2=80=99ve noted before, is that CBS News is a fading division in a=
 fading network within a fading company. If the ratings declines continue a=
pace, the revenue hits
to the bottom line will undo whatever cost savings the network sought to ac=
hieve in the most recent overhaul. The biggest bummer here, however, is sli=
ghtly more nuanced. Television news is a historically risk-averse medium de=
eply in need of reinvention. Yes, Owens=E2=80=99 new format innovation seem=
s like a dud, but one hopes that it won=E2=80=99t prevent others from tryin=
g things out, too. After all, we all know what fate will meet the status qu=
o.

