r witnessed a scene
like the disgusting display that occurred in the Oval Office today.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Whatever one made of Elon=E2=80=99s appearance, it =
was indisputably abnormal <em>and</em> historic. Fittingly, the images went=
 viral on social media, and led practically all the major news sites on Tue=
sday afternoon. At 6:30 p.m., ABC=E2=80=99s <strong>David Muir </strong>beg=
an <em>World News Tonight </em>with =E2=80=9Cbreaking news=E2=80=9D of the =
=E2=80=9Cremarkable scene
just a short time ago: Elon Musk holding court in the Oval Office.=E2=80=9D=
 Likewise, NBC=E2=80=99s <strong>Lester Holt </strong>led the <em>Nightly N=
ews</em> with Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cmajor moment with President Trump in =
the Oval Office.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Notably, CBS took a differe=
nt tack, delivered by <em>Evening News</em> co-host <strong>John Dickerson<=
/strong>: =E2=80=9CWe begin tonight with a classic question that has come t=
o symbolize a crisis in
American education: Why can=E2=80=99t Johnny read?=E2=80=9D The package was=
 pegged to national test scores demonstrating that students remain at pre-p=
andemic reading levels despite hundreds of billions of dollars in federal p=
andemic relief funds. After the six-minute segment, Dickerson and his co-ho=
st <strong>Maurice DuBois </strong>offered a =E2=80=9Croundup=E2=80=9D of t=
he day=E2=80=99s headlines, noting Russia=E2=80=99s release of an American =
prisoner (15 seconds) and Musk=E2=80=99s Oval appearance (22 seconds), befo=
re moving on to a two-minute
conversation with CBS=E2=80=99s chief medical correspondent about Avian flu=
=2E</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=E2=80=9CWhy can=E2=80=99t Johnny read?=E2=80=9D is a=
 play on the 1955 best-selling book about flaws in U.S. education, of cours=
e. But within CBS=E2=80=99s Washington bureau, it has become fodder for a b=
roader internal critique of <em>Evening News</em>=E2=80=94and, indeed, the =
network itself=E2=80=94under C.E.O. <strong>Wendy McMahon </strong>and <em>=
Evening News </em>supervising
producer <strong>Bill Owens</strong>. =E2=80=9CWhy can=E2=80=99t John read<=
em> the news</em>?=E2=80=9D one CBS News correspondent asked me, referring =
to Dickerson. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s tough to watch,=E2=80=9D a former CBS N=
ews insider said. =E2=80=9CI appreciate doing something new. I really do=E2=
=80=A6 [but] Bill and I have different theories of the case.=E2=80=9D</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">Since becoming CBS News C.E.O. in 2023, McMahon has entruste=
d the network=E2=80=99s editorial vision to Owens, which is
understandable given his tenure at <em>60 Minutes</em>, where he has served=
 as executive producer since 2019. Last August, she expanded Owens=E2=80=99=
 remit to include <em>Evening News</em>, the perennial third-place nightly =
news broadcast. Owens immediately conceived of a new editorial strategy pri=
oritizing longer enterprise packages, human interest stories, and ample wea=
ther coverage over the usual digest of the day=E2=80=99s big headlines. He =
also asked McMahon to delicately transfer <strong>Norah O=E2=80=99Donnell
</strong>off the anchor=E2=80=99s desk in order to install Dickerson and Du=
Bois, making <em>Evening News </em>the first nightly broadcast to do away w=
ith a single anchor, <strong>Cronkite</strong> nostalgia be damned.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Perha=
ps none of these were great ideas, but they were at least an attempt to sha=
ke up a stale format whose decline mirrors the demise of linear television.=
 While it=E2=80=99s obviously<em> very</em> early=E2=80=94the newly revampe=
d
<em>Evening News </em>only debuted in late January=E2=80=94the show has alr=
eady seen its ratings markedly decline. In its second week, its total audie=
nce was down 5 percent from the prior week, and down 9 percent year over ye=
ar. Meanwhile, the programming strategy has confounded many network insider=
s=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just not good, sorry=E2=80=9D one said=E2=
=80=94while irking several of the Washington-based correspondents, who fear=
 the loss of what precious little real estate still exists for their work.=
