red something <em>other</em> than headlines that audiences are already
familiar with by 6:30 p.m. If <em>60 Minutes </em>and CBS <em>Sunday Mornin=
gs </em>have proven successful with the newsmagazine format, the logic goes=
, then why not <em>Evening News</em>? The longer packages seemed designed f=
or social media and YouTube, which is where the future of the format reside=
s.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Then again, <em>Evening News </em>remains a pr=
ofitable enterprise watched by nearly 5 million
people, and, as most media veterans see it, there=E2=80=99s a reason why th=
at=E2=80=99s the case. Alas, Owens=E2=80=99 newsmagazine format =E2=80=9Cdo=
es not work at that time,=E2=80=9D one longtime media exec said. =E2=80=9CT=
here=E2=80=99s a reason formats work where they work.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">In any event, the frustrations over <em>Evening News </em>are=
 compounding the larger problems at CBS News amid the recent <em>60 Minutes=
 </em>edit
